Review: A deconstructed soap opera that verges on anti-cinema, I’ve never seen a film that keeps me so engaged while constantly removing the comfort of voyeurism. The terrible lighting, exaggerated performances, awkward editing, jarring score. It all feels carefully engineered to discomfort you, which emulates Elizabeth’s experience trying and failing to understand Gracie’s character (a brilliant “one dimensional” antagonist) in a way that ironically feels wholly cinematic. The film being in conversation with PERSONA and BLOW-OUT is not cheap homage, but…
Giving this an upgrade to the four, since something obviously keeps me coming back! Although, watching it with Sienna kinda felt like I was getting cucked.

Movie: Art-House America: Twenty-Five Years of the Walter Reade
The Hunger Games: The Ballad of Songbirds & Snakes
Review: Probably my favorite since the first one, which I believe is due to the exaggerated, steampunk vibe that takes a lot more risks whereas the original trilogy tried its best to stay grounded. Interestingly, the strange tone of it all makes the subject matter even more disturbing.
Probably the darkest film from Payne I’ve seen yet, but also the funniest. I’d love to see another entry similar to this, but I don’t think the cultural climate would allow it.
The visual language here was really refreshing. Excited to see Dream Scenario!

Movie: The Taking of Pelham One Two Three
Review: My fascination with this stems mostly from the fact that it could be described as an anti-heist movie. Nobody gets robbed. The “action” is brief, obscured, and unexciting. Our hero isn’t Al Pacino’s Vincent Hanna, a dedicated lawman. It’s Walter Matthau’s Zachary Garber, an NYC Transit Police Lieutenant (among the most useless jobs on Earth.) Matthau skillfully brings a working man’s lack of enthusiasm to the character. We know this isn’t some rush he’s addicted to, some grand stroke of…
The most recent iteration of Kurosawa’s lone samurai, to my knowledge.
